  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 60-65°F for Optimal Tannin Balance</strong> - Merlot's moderate tannin structure requires careful temperature control. Too warm (above 68°F) and the alcohol dominates the delicate plum and chocolate notes; too cold (below 58°F) and the tannins become harsh, masking Merlot's signature velvety mouthfeel. Use a wine thermometer and aim for the lower end with younger, fruit-forward styles.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Based on Vintage and Style, Not Blanket Rules</strong> - Young, concentrated Merlots from producers like Château Le Pin or Duckhorn benefit from 45-60 minutes of decanting to soften tannins and integrate oak. However, mature Right Bank Merlots (15+ years) should only be decanted briefly (15 minutes) to preserve their evolved tertiary aromas of leather, truffle, and dried herbs that define aged Merlot complexity.</li>

