<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on quality, region, and winemaking style. Understanding these differences is crucial for proper cellar management and optimal drinking experiences.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Everyday Merlots</strong> (under $20) are crafted for immediate consumption and should be enjoyed within 2-3 years of vintage. These wines emphasize fresh fruit and soft tannins that don't benefit from extended aging.</p>

<p><strong>Premium estate Merlots</strong> ($30-60) from regions like Napa Valley or Walla Walla can develop beautifully for 8-12 years. Right Bank Bordeaux Merlots, particularly from Saint-Émilion Grand Cru estates, can age gracefully for 15-20 years or more.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Young Merlot displays vibrant plum and blackberry fruit with prominent, sometimes grippy tannins. As it ages, the tannins polymerize and soften, while primary fruit flavors evolve into complex secondary notes of leather, tobacco, dried herbs, and earth. The wine's texture becomes silkier, and tertiary aromas of forest floor, truffle, and cedar emerge after 7-10 years.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most premium Merlots reach their peak between years 5-8, when fruit concentration balances with developed complexity. However, exceptional vintages from top producers can continue improving for decades.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store Merlot at consistent 55-60°F with 60-70% humidity. Keep bottles on their side to maintain cork moisture. Avoid temperature fluctuations and direct light, which can cause premature oxidation and color degradation.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged Merlot develops brick-red edges while maintaining core color intensity. The wine should smell clean with evolved aromas—never vinegary, musty, or excessively oxidized. Healthy aged Merlot retains balanced acidity and integrated alcohol, while spoiled wine tastes flat, overly sharp, or shows obvious flaws like cork taint or volatile acidity.</p>

